def subdomain(typ, symbol, length):
    today = date.today()
    today = today.strftime("%m/%d/%y")
    subdoma="{0}{1}/historical-prices/download?num_rows={2}&range_days={2}&endDate={3}"
    subdomain = subdoma.format(typ, symbol, length, today)
    return subdomain
def header_function(subdomain):
    hdrs = {"user-agent": "Mozilla/5.0 (Windows NT 10.0; Win64)"}
    return hdrs
def scrape_page(url, header):
    page = requests.get(url, headers=header)
    print(page.status_code)
    return page.text
def format_page(symbol, typ, length):
    base_url = 'https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/'
    sub = subdomain(typ, symbol, length)
    header = header_function(sub)
    url = base_url + sub
    price_history = scrape_page(url, header)
    history = [[i[0:8]] + [float(j) for j in i.split(",")[1:]] for i in price_history.split("\n")[1:]]
    history = history[::-1]
    return history

Now going to write functions that will get the SPY, TLT, GLD, UUP, and VIX for every day since beginning of 2005. Note: UUP did not start until 2007, but I felt that analysis could be done using the other ones still. The stocks are inputted into a pandas dataframe. The number of days used is 5939, which is days since Jan 1 2005, is updated as I work on project.

In [13]:
def formatHistory(data, symbol):
    hist = pd.DataFrame(data)
    hist = hist.rename(columns={0: "Date"})
    hist["Date"] = pd.to_datetime(hist["Date"], format='%m/%d/%y')
    hist = hist.set_index('Date')
    hist = hist.drop(columns = [1, 2, 3])
    if(symbol != 'VIX'):
        hist = hist.drop(columns = [5])
    hist = hist.rename(columns={4: symbol})
    return hist

In [16]:
def getStocks(numDays):
    dat1 = format_page('SPY', 'etf/', numDays)
    SPY = formatHistory(dat1, 'SPY')
    sleep(3)
    dat2 = format_page('VIX', 'index/', numDays)
    VIX = formatHistory(dat2, 'VIX')
    sleep(3)
    dat3 = format_page('TLT', 'etf/', numDays)
    TLT = formatHistory(dat3, 'TLT')
    sleep(3)
    dat4 = format_page('GLD', 'etf/', numDays)
    GLD = formatHistory(dat4, 'GLD')
    sleep(3)
    dat5 = format_page('UUP', 'etf/', numDays)
    UUP = formatHistory(dat5, 'UUP')
    VIX = VIX.loc[SPY.index]
    stocks = pd.concat([SPY, VIX, TLT, GLD, UUP], axis = 1)
    stocks = stocks.reset_index()
    return stocks

The following gives the functions that will be used to calculate the z-score for each day using the previous 80 days. For the first 80 days, I will use the most possible days available, and will predefine the z-scores for the first and second days as 0. It should be noted that for the first 80 days, these results will need to be interpreted with caution.

In [23]:
def getWindow(ETF, day, N = 80):
    ''' Default of N is 80
    indexing of days starts at 0,
    but for 81st day, put 81 as day 
    '''
    indAdj = N + 1
    close = ETF[day - indAdj:day - 1]
    newClose = ETF[day - 1]
    return [close, newClose]
In [24]:
def zScore(ETF, day, N = 80):
    ''' Default of N is 80
    indexing of days starts at 0,
    but for 81st day, put 81 as day 
    '''
    close, newClose = getWindow(ETF, day, N)
    mean = fmean(close)
    sd = stdev(close)
    z = (newClose - mean) / sd
    return z

The following is a test for normality for one of the 80 day intervals. However, using the Central Limit Theorem (I have knowledge of this from prior math classes), if the sample size is large enough, usually n=30n=30, then the distribution of the sample mean will approach a normal distribution. Therefore, when using sample sizes of 80, a z-score can be used. A quick google search found that there was no simple and efficient way to evaluate where a current stock price was in compared to previous days close.

When I looked at these dates, I found that they were not exactly reflective of the actual dates of crashes. I therefore went to internet sources to see if there is a list of market crahses with start and end dates. In my research, I found that changes of 10% were significant (https://www.thebalance.com/stock-market-crash-examples-cause-impact-3305864#:~:text=A%20stock%20market%20crash%20is,a%20few%20days%2C%20of%20trading.&text=A%20crash%20is%20more%20sudden,%2C%20weeks%2C%20or%20even%20months), as changes less than that may be corrected within a shorter period of time and will not result in a loss of assets in the long run. The source I used for the crashes is: https://awealthofcommonsense.com/2021/02/a-short-history-of-u-s-stock-market-corrections-bear-markets/

I next wanted to set up the functions that will compute the z-scores.

In [30]:
def makeZScores(ETF):
    scores = [0, 0]
    for i in range(3, len(ETF) + 1):
        if(i < 81):
            z = zScore(ETF, i, i - 1)
            scores = scores + [z]
        else:
            z = zScore(ETF, i)
            scores = scores + [z]
    return scores

Now going to set up the correlations. 126 days was used, as since the sample size is large enough, it can be used.

In [496]:
def getWindow2(ETF, day, N = 127):
    ''' Default of N is 81
    indexing of days starts at 0,
    but for 81st day, put 81 as day 
    '''
    close = ETF[day - N + 1:day + 1]
    return close
def correlation(ETF1, ETF2, day, N = 126):
    fund1 = list(getWindow2(ETF1, day, N + 1))
    fund2 = list(getWindow2(ETF2, day, N + 1))
    xChanges = []
    yChanges = []
    for i in range(len(fund1) - 1):
        xdiff = (fund1[i + 1] - fund1[i])/fund1[i]
        ydiff = (fund2[i + 1] - fund2[i])/fund2[i]
        xChanges = xChanges + [xdiff]
        yChanges = yChanges + [ydiff]
    r = stats.pearsonr(xChanges, yChanges)
    return r[0]

def makeCorrelations(ETF1, ETF2):
    scores = [0]
    for i in range(2, len(ETF1) + 1):
        if(i < 126):
            r = correlation(ETF1, ETF2, i, i)
            scores = scores + [r]
        else:
            r = correlation(ETF1, ETF2, i, 126)
            scores = scores + [r]
    return scores

In [55]:
def plotCrash(cr, stock):
    start, end = cr
    end = end + 1
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = (6.4, 4.8))
    crash = stock.iloc[start - 10: end]
    plt.plot(crash['Date'], crash['SPY'])
    plt.setp(ax.get_xticklabels(), rotation=45)
    plt.ylabel('Dollars')
    plt.show()

Function to get a set of 10 z-scores

In [83]:
def rangeZScores(ETF, end):
    scores = []
    for i in range(end + 1 - 10, end + 1):
        z = zScore(ETF, i)
        scores = scores + [z]
    return scores

In [120]:
def plotZ(crash, stock, symbol):
    ends = [i[0] for i in crashes]
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = (6.4, 4.8))
    j = 1
    for i in ends:
        til = 'Crash' + str(j)
        plt.plot(rangeZScores(stock, i), label = til)
        j = j + 1
    tit = 'Z-score for ' + symbol
    plt.ylabel(tit)
    plt.legend()
    plt.xlabel('Days Before Each Crash, 0 is 10 days before start of crash')
    plt.show()

It definetely seems that for the 10 days before a crash, the z-scores do fall within a certain range for each ETF. Will now use mannywhitneyu to see if these z-scores are statistically significantly different when compared to a random selestion of 70 point from each ETF.

In [607]:
def getAllZ(stock, crash):
    ends = [i[0] for i in crash]
    allZ = []
    for i in ends:
        allZ = allZ + rangeZScores(stock, i) 
    return allZ
In [608]:
spyZ = getAllZ(stocks['SPY'], crashes)
randSpyZ = [zScore(stocks['SPY'], i) for i in random.sample(range(81, 4092), 70)]

Less than 0.05, can assume that there is a statistitically significant difference between the z-scores before crash and a random 70 days. Will now use all of the days from 81 to the end.

def zScoreSummary(stocks, allStocks, crash, symbol):
    crashZ = getAllZ(stocks, crash)
    dates = list(range(81, 697)) + list(range(1051, 1336)) + list(range(1384, 1593)) + list(range(1700, 2729)) + list(range(2796, 3290)) + list(range(3298, 3454)) + list(range(3518, 3808)) + list(range(3830, len(allStocks) + 1))
    if(symbol == 'UUP'):
        dates = list(range(81, 161)) + list(range(515, 800)) + list(range(848, 1057)) + list(range(1164, 2193)) + list(range(2260, 2754)) + list(range(2762, 2918)) + list(range(2982, 3272)) + list(range(3294, len(allStocks) + 1))    
    allZ = [zScore(allStocks, i) for i in dates]
    test_statistic, p_value = stats.mannwhitneyu(crashZ, allZ)
    print(symbol)
    print()
    print("p-value is: ", p_value)
    print()
    print('5 number summary for Z-scores before Crashes for ', symbol)
    print("Min: ", np.min(crashZ))
    print("Max: ", np.max(crashZ))
    print("STD: ", np.std(crashZ))
    print("Mean: ", np.mean(crashZ))
    print("Median: ", np.median(crashZ))
    print()
    print('5 number summary for Z-scores for all of ', symbol)
    print("Min: ", np.min(allZ))
    print("Max: ", np.max(allZ))
    print("STD: ", np.std(allZ))
    print("Mean: ", np.mean(allZ))
    print("Median: ", np.median(allZ))
    data = list([crashZ, allZ])
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    ax.boxplot(data)
    ax.set_title('Z-scores for before crashes vs. All of ' + symbol)
    ax.set_ylabel('z-score')
    xticklabels=['Before Crashes', 'All of ' + symbol ]
    ax.set_xticklabels(xticklabels)
    ax.yaxis.grid(True)
    plt.show()

def rangeCorr(ETF1, ETF2, end):
    scores = []
    for i in range(end + 1 - 10, end + 1):
        c = correlation(ETF1, ETF2, i)
        scores = scores + [c]
    return scores 
def plotCorr(crash, stock1, stock2, symbol1, symbol2):
    ends = [i[0] for i in crashes]
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize = (6.4, 4.8))
    j = 1
    for i in ends:
        til = 'Crash' + str(j)
        plt.plot(rangeCorr(stock1, stock2, i), label = til)
        j = j + 1
    tit = 'Correlation for ' + symbol1 + "/" + symbol2
    plt.ylabel(tit)
    plt.legend()
    plt.xlabel('Days Before Each Crash, 0 is 10 days before start of crash')
    plt.show()

def getAllCor(stock1, stock2, crash):
    ends = [i[0] for i in crash]
    allC = []
    for i in ends:
        allC = allC + rangeCorr(stock1, stock2, i) 
    return allC

def beforeVafterZ(stocks, crash, symbol):
    crashB = getAllZ(stocks, crash)
    crashA = getAllZAfter(stocks, crash)
    test_statistic, p_value = stats.mannwhitneyu(crashB, crashA)
    print(symbol)
    print()
    print("p-value is: ", p_value)
    print()
    print('5 number summary for Z-scores before Crashes for ', symbol)
    print("Min: ", np.min(crashB))
    print("Max: ", np.max(crashB))
    print("STD: ", np.std(crashB))
    print("Mean: ", np.mean(crashB))
    print("Median: ", np.median(crashB))
    print()
    print('5 number summary for Z-scores after Crashes for ', symbol)
    print("Min: ", np.min(crashA))
    print("Max: ", np.max(crashA))
    print("STD: ", np.std(crashA))
    print("Mean: ", np.mean(crashA))
    print("Median: ", np.median(crashA))
    data = list([crashB, crashA])
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    ax.boxplot(data)
    ax.set_title('Z-scores for before crashes vs. after for ' + symbol)
    ax.set_ylabel('z-score')
    xticklabels=['Before Crashes', 'After Crashes' ]
    ax.set_xticklabels(xticklabels)
    ax.yaxis.grid(True)
    plt.show()

def beforeVafterCorr(stocks1, stocks2, crash, symbol1, symbol2):
    crashB = getAllCor(stocks1, stocks2, crash)
    crashA = getAllCorAfter(stocks1, stocks2, crash)
    test_statistic, p_value = stats.mannwhitneyu(crashB, crashA)
    print(symbol1, "/", symbol2)
    print()
    print("p-value is: ", p_value)
    print()
    print('5 number summary for Correlations before Crashes for ', symbol1, "/", symbol2)
    print("Min: ", np.min(crashB))
    print("Max: ", np.max(crashB))
    print("STD: ", np.std(crashB))
    print("Mean: ", np.mean(crashB))
    print("Median: ", np.median(crashB))
    print()
    print('5 number summary for Correlations after Crashes for ', symbol1, "/", symbol2)
    print("Min: ", np.min(crashA))
    print("Max: ", np.max(crashA))
    print("STD: ", np.std(crashA))
    print("Mean: ", np.mean(crashA))
    print("Median: ", np.median(crashA))
    data = list([crashB, crashA])
    fig, ax = plt.subplots()
    ax.boxplot(data)
    ax.set_title('Correlations for before crashes vs. after for ' + symbol1 + "/" + symbol2)
    ax.set_ylabel('Correlation')
    xticklabels=['Before Crashes', 'After Crashes' ]
    ax.set_xticklabels(xticklabels)
    ax.yaxis.grid(True)
    plt.show()
